>Hi All:

>I am upgrading to a 100 MHz Pentium and my dealer wants to put in an Intel 
>Zappa motherboard.  The problems:

>1)  Documentation says this mobo maxes out at 90 MH
>2)  The L2 cache is 20 ns.  Isn't the 100 MHz Pentium supposed to need 15 ns 
>cache?
>3)  On boot, the BIOS says it is AMI BIOS, ver 1.000 ... from 1992.  Is this 
>strange?  Shouldn't the BIOS date be 1995?
>The Zappa uses the Triton chipset.
>Thanks.  Bob.

I just installed an Intel advanced zp ed (zappa) in my system.  You can run a 
P100 in 2x mode at 50mhz, but you are only running the PCI at 25mhz.  I read a 
hint from someone in the Intel newsgroup that there was and undocumented 
setting to put you at 66mhz by setting the switches 7 & 8 to off & on 
respectively, or opposite the 60mhz setting.  You then have to set switch 6 to 
off to set the multi to 1.5x and switch 1 to on to set the isa bus to 1/4 
since its coming off the 33mhz bus speed.  I tried this with mine and the 
processor speed in various benchmarks went up slightly, but my i/o sensitive 
benchmarks for video and disk speed went up 15-20%. As for the BIOS, you got 
me as mine is 2\95 and version 1.????? I,d have to reboot to check the #.  As 
for the cache, I don't think in the real world the speed increase would be 
very noticeable, even with synchronous sram. I've had no problems using the 
undocumented settings and the machine is quite fast.
